WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.396 --> 00:00:02.151
Diane: Thanks for joining us.

00:00:02.151 --> 00:00:03.263
I'm Diane Rehm.

00:00:03.263 --> 00:00:06.864
Harvard MBA and former Hedge Fund manager,

00:00:06.864 --> 00:00:11.137
Salman Khan has become an Internet sensation.

00:00:11.137 --> 00:00:13.820
He's the founder of Khan Academy,

00:00:13.820 --> 00:00:19.402
a nonprofit organization that provides free online tutorials

00:00:19.402 --> 00:00:23.569
on subjects including math, science and history.

00:00:23.569 --> 00:00:28.319
Today, his videos attract more than 5,000,000 users a month.

00:00:28.319 --> 00:00:31.763
They're used in classrooms around the world.

00:00:31.763 --> 00:00:37.814
In a new book, Khan encourages us to rethink our current education system

00:00:37.814 --> 00:00:40.993
and offers ways to improve it.

00:00:40.993 --> 00:00:46.888
It's titled, The One World Schoolhouse Education Reimagined.

00:00:46.888 --> 00:00:49.565
Salman Khan joins me in the studio.

00:00:49.565 --> 00:00:52.998
I invite you to be part of the program.

00:00:52.998 --> 00:00:57.576
Call us on 800-433-8850.

00:00:57.576 --> 00:01:03.513
Send us your email to drshow@wamu.org.

00:01:03.513 --> 00:01:07.260
Follow us on Facebook or Twitter.

00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:08.327
Good morning to you.

00:01:08.327 --> 00:01:10.237
It's good to have you here.

00:01:10.237 --> 00:01:11.326
Salman: Honored to be here.

00:01:11.326 --> 00:01:19.264
Diane: You know, I saw a piece you did with 60 Minutes.

00:01:19.264 --> 00:01:22.513
I was so impressed.

00:01:22.513 --> 00:01:25.762
Tell us how all this began.

00:01:25.762 --> 00:01:31.132
Salman: It was, as was introduced, in 2004 I was an analyst at Hedge Fund,

00:01:31.132 --> 00:01:31.889
not a manager.

00:01:31.889 --> 00:01:33.507
Otherwise I would be dressed a little bit better.

00:01:33.507 --> 00:01:36.389
Diane: (laughs) I think you look just fine.

00:01:36.389 --> 00:01:37.638
Salman: (laughs) Thank you.

00:01:37.638 --> 00:01:40.374
I had just gotten married.

00:01:40.374 --> 00:01:46.300
I was in Boston and some family was visiting in New Orleans, after the wedding.

00:01:46.300 --> 00:01:52.130
In particular my cousin Nadia, who is 12 years old, a very bright young girl.

00:01:52.130 --> 00:01:53.745
I was showing her the universities and saying,

00:01:53.745 --> 00:01:57.267
"Hey, I think you should go to MIT, major in computer science"

00:01:57.267 --> 00:02:01.867
"and eventually turn that into a career at maybe a Hedge Fund."

00:02:01.867 --> 00:02:08.993
Her mom actually told me that, "It's nice that you're mentoring Nadia"

00:02:08.993 --> 00:02:11.976
"and you're trying to make her go in your footsteps and all of these great things,"

00:02:11.976 --> 00:02:15.597
"but she's actually having trouble with mathematics."

00:02:15.597 --> 00:02:18.467
I had trouble believing that and I talked to Nadia about it.

00:02:18.467 --> 00:02:20.226
I said, "What's going on?"

00:02:20.226 --> 00:02:21.105
Diane: What's going on?

00:02:21.105 --> 00:02:26.368
Salman: She said, "I took a placement exam and I just don't get unit conversion;"

00:02:26.368 --> 00:02:30.287
"ounces to gallons, meters, kilometers, that type of thing."

00:02:30.287 --> 00:02:33.743
I told her, "I can see how that can be confusing,"

00:02:33.743 --> 00:02:37.787
"but we've had conversations in the last 2 days that are deeper than that"

00:02:37.787 --> 00:02:39.370
"and I think that you can overcome that."

00:02:39.370 --> 00:02:41.787
I think that she thought this was just a pep talk

00:02:41.787 --> 00:02:47.481
and that her cousin didn't really understand that she really didn't get math.

00:02:47.481 --> 00:02:49.995
I said, "How about when you go back to New Orleans,"

00:02:49.995 --> 00:02:53.743
"everyday after work for me, school for you, we get on the phone."

00:02:53.743 --> 00:02:56.594
"It's extra work for you, but if you're up for it, I'm up for it."

00:02:56.594 --> 00:02:59.870
"I'm convinced you can do this."

00:02:59.870 --> 00:03:03.182
She agreed and so we started working together.

00:03:03.182 --> 00:03:06.183
Long story short, the first month was hard,

00:03:06.183 --> 00:03:11.767
but once she got into it, she got up to speed, started getting ahead of the curve.

00:03:11.767 --> 00:03:14.496
The same girl, who in 6th grade, thought she couldn't get units,

00:03:14.496 --> 00:03:19.618
ended up taking calculus her sophomore year in high school.

00:03:19.618 --> 00:03:23.933
Then, I started teaching, working with her younger brothers.

00:03:23.933 --> 00:03:27.433
Fast forward about 2 years, word had gotten around in the family

00:03:27.433 --> 00:03:31.017
that free tutoring was happening and I had this cohort of students.

00:03:31.017 --> 00:03:33.933
I had started writing software for them, that was my background.

00:03:33.933 --> 00:03:37.245
Giving them problems and see what they knew and what they didn't know,

00:03:37.245 --> 00:03:40.510
so that I could make my tutorials more productive.

00:03:40.510 --> 00:03:42.995
I was showing this to a friend and I was kind of saying, "This is great."

00:03:42.995 --> 00:03:47.809
By this point I had moved out to Silicon Valley in Northern California.

00:03:47.809 --> 00:03:51.142
It was difficult now, now that I have 10 or 15 of these kids around the country

00:03:51.142 --> 00:03:52.871
that I'm trying to coordinate with.

00:03:52.871 --> 00:03:57.058
It was my friend who said, "Why don't you make some of your tutorials on You Tube."

00:03:57.058 --> 00:03:59.496
I thought it was a horrible idea.

00:03:59.496 --> 00:04:06.608
I said, "You Tube is for cats playing piano, not serious mathematics."

00:04:06.608 --> 00:04:08.532
I gave it a shot.

00:04:08.532 --> 00:04:13.248
My cousins famously told me they liked me better on You Tube than in person.

00:04:13.248 --> 00:04:15.779
I kept going.

00:04:15.779 --> 00:04:19.871
It didn't take too long to realize that people who are not my cousins were watching.

00:04:19.871 --> 00:04:26.532
Diane: At what point did you decide you could actually quit your work,

00:04:26.532 --> 00:04:34.999
quit your job and devote yourself to this kind of creation of tutorials?

00:04:34.999 --> 00:04:36.692
Salman: The first video was in 2006.

00:04:36.692 --> 00:04:37.989
Diane: Right.

00:04:37.989 --> 00:04:41.774
Salman: It wasn't until 2009 that the traffic was getting so large

00:04:41.774 --> 00:04:43.623
and I was getting so many letters.

00:04:43.623 --> 00:04:47.106
I was having trouble frankly keeping up with all of this as a hobby.

00:04:47.106 --> 00:04:52.120
I was even sneaking a few moments in in my day job to tackle some of this.

00:04:52.120 --> 00:04:55.874
I sat down with my wife and I set it up as a not-for-profit,

00:04:55.874 --> 00:04:57.874
saying, "The mission should be to reach as many people,"

00:04:57.874 --> 00:05:00.978
"empower as many people here."

00:05:00.978 --> 00:05:03.522
I had never started a not-for-profit before.

00:05:03.522 --> 00:05:06.734
I said, "Someone should realize there's a high social return on investment here,"

00:05:06.734 --> 00:05:09.748
"an almost infinite social return on investment here."

00:05:09.748 --> 00:05:11.987
I quit my job.

00:05:11.987 --> 00:05:15.729
My wife and I, we kind of agreed, we have about a year of savings

00:05:15.729 --> 00:05:17.987
and that'll be what -

00:05:17.987 --> 00:05:19.532
I'll give it a shot.

00:05:19.532 --> 00:05:21.782
9 months into it, it started to get a little bit taxing.

00:05:21.782 --> 00:05:24.773
I started thinking about updating my resume a bit.

00:05:24.773 --> 00:05:28.870
Luckily, we were able to get funding.

00:05:28.870 --> 00:05:30.109
Diane: Where?

00:05:30.109 --> 00:05:32.871
Salman: The first funding came from, her name is Ann Doerr,

00:05:32.871 --> 00:05:35.523
I got a $10,000 donation online.

00:05:35.523 --> 00:05:38.772
Actually, she mailed that one.

00:05:38.772 --> 00:05:41.770
Before I was getting these $5 and $10 donations from people all over the world,

00:05:41.770 --> 00:05:44.613
which was tremendous and it was helping.

00:05:44.613 --> 00:05:50.609
I told Ann, "If we were a physical school, you would now have a building named after you."

00:05:50.609 --> 00:05:52.623
When she found out that I was living off of savings,

00:05:52.623 --> 00:05:56.519
she really stepped up and gave a larger donation,

00:05:56.519 --> 00:05:58.972
so that I could support myself with a salary.

00:05:58.972 --> 00:06:02.249
Then, a few months later I actually got a text message from Ann.

00:06:02.249 --> 00:06:04.999
She was at a conference where Bill Gates was speaking.

00:06:04.999 --> 00:06:07.623
She texted me saying, "Bill Gates is on stage right now,"

00:06:07.623 --> 00:06:11.758
"telling everyone in the audience that he uses the Khan Academy for his kids,"

00:06:11.758 --> 00:06:14.622
"he uses it himself."

00:06:14.622 --> 00:06:16.496
That was a exciting and surreal moment.

00:06:16.496 --> 00:06:19.888
Diane: Breakthrough moment, I must say.

00:06:19.888 --> 00:06:25.263
Then, Bill Gates and the Gates Foundation came through

00:06:25.263 --> 00:06:30.187
with a large contribution and then others followed.

00:06:30.187 --> 00:06:32.367
Salman: Yeah, they've been our largest funder.

00:06:32.367 --> 00:06:35.168
Google, also at that time, kind of stepped out of the woodwork

00:06:35.168 --> 00:06:36.668
and gave a significant donation.

00:06:36.668 --> 00:06:39.502
There have been several other folks.

00:06:39.502 --> 00:06:43.065
A lot of them in kind of the tech world, who have come out to support this.

00:06:43.065 --> 00:06:51.815
Diane: How has the whole vision changed since you first began?

00:06:51.815 --> 00:06:55.565
Salman: It's been a very organic process,

00:06:55.565 --> 00:06:58.360
literally just starting with tutorials for cousins.

00:06:58.360 --> 00:07:01.366
As we've grown and even when we got that first funding,

00:07:01.366 --> 00:07:04.508
I always imagined Khan Academy of being the supplementary thing.

00:07:04.508 --> 00:07:07.899
Like most people, you read news stories

00:07:07.899 --> 00:07:10.149
and you become cynical about the system, so to speak,

00:07:10.149 --> 00:07:12.595
and I never thought that we would be part of it.

00:07:12.595 --> 00:07:16.272
Right from the get go a public school district reached out to us, in California and said,

00:07:16.272 --> 00:07:19.521
"We're fascinated by some of the work y'all are doing."

00:07:19.521 --> 00:07:23.748
"How would you see this being used in a 5th grade math classroom?"

00:07:23.748 --> 00:07:29.600
We said, "These tools, the software, the videos allow every student"

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:30.737
"to work at their own pace."

00:07:30.737 --> 00:07:33.620
"It allows the information delivery component of learning"

00:07:33.620 --> 00:07:36.119
"to happen whenever a student wants it."

00:07:36.119 --> 00:07:39.619
"In our mind, it frees up the classroom to do more interactive things."

00:07:39.619 --> 00:07:41.948
In the ideal world, kids would work at their own pace,

00:07:41.948 --> 00:07:45.726
teachers would get realtime information about where they all are.

00:07:45.726 --> 00:07:48.367
Then, they could use that information to do focus interventions,

00:07:48.367 --> 00:07:52.222
to lead projects, to have the students tutor each other.

00:07:52.222 --> 00:07:55.519
Within 2 weeks they said, "This is a good idea."

00:07:55.519 --> 00:07:57.436
"Let's try it with 4 classrooms."

00:07:57.436 --> 00:08:02.111
Since then, they've extended it to every classroom in the district, 5th through 8th grade.

00:08:02.111 --> 00:08:04.857
Beyond that it's been 20,000 classrooms around the country.

00:08:04.857 --> 00:08:11.436
Diane: Is that in any and all subjects, or just in math?

00:08:11.436 --> 00:08:15.770
Salman: The site we have, especially the videos, are fairly broad,

00:08:15.770 --> 00:08:17.269
especially in math and science.

00:08:17.269 --> 00:08:21.248
They go all the way to college level biology and chemistry.

00:08:21.248 --> 00:08:22.874
This pilot that we started with Los Altos,

00:08:22.874 --> 00:08:25.621
and this is where a lot of our interactivity is right now,

00:08:25.621 --> 00:08:28.248
was in mathematics.

00:08:28.248 --> 00:08:29.871
Diane: But, now?

00:08:29.871 --> 00:08:31.984
Salman: Now, we're starting to look beyond that.

00:08:31.984 --> 00:08:34.499
We've recently launched a computer science on the site,

00:08:34.499 --> 00:08:36.999
which shows kind of the creative side of computer science.

00:08:36.999 --> 00:08:39.247
Kids create portfolios of their work.

00:08:39.247 --> 00:08:42.873
Los Altos in interested now in using that as part of computer science.

00:08:42.873 --> 00:08:46.750
This is for elementary school kids to start to learn to program.

00:08:46.750 --> 00:08:50.240
Our long-term goal is, as we have more content on the site,

00:08:50.240 --> 00:08:52.243
both videos and interactive content,

00:08:52.243 --> 00:08:56.653
we think that elements of this can be introduced into almost any subject.

00:08:56.653 --> 00:09:01.499
Diane: Do you have family in addition to your wife?

00:09:01.499 --> 00:09:03.500
Do you have small children?

00:09:03.500 --> 00:09:05.402
Salman: Yes I have a 1-year-old and a 3-year-old.

00:09:05.402 --> 00:09:07.365
Diane: Oh my.

00:09:07.365 --> 00:09:10.998
Is your wife staying at home with these children

00:09:10.998 --> 00:09:16.122
or is she out of the house and working there as well?

00:09:16.122 --> 00:09:19.664
Salman: My wife is a physician and she is working 3 days a week.

00:09:19.664 --> 00:09:23.240
We also have my mother in law who lives with us.

00:09:23.240 --> 00:09:26.262
We have kind of a hybrid solution going on.

00:09:26.262 --> 00:09:29.429
Diane: How do you make your income?

00:09:29.429 --> 00:09:32.511
Salman: I now get a salary from the Khan Academy.

00:09:32.511 --> 00:09:40.038
Diane: That's really fantastic in terms of trying to help other people.

00:09:40.038 --> 00:09:44.122
You've done this clearly as a nonprofit.

00:09:44.122 --> 00:09:49.125
Are you still offering these videos free of charge?

00:09:49.125 --> 00:09:54.538
Salman: Yeah. In 2007, when I was first filling out that paper work for the IRS,

00:09:54.538 --> 00:09:58.123
they say admission statement for your not-for-profit.

00:09:58.123 --> 00:09:59.874
I said, "Let me think of something."

00:09:59.874 --> 00:10:02.276
I thought about it for about 4 minutes and I said,

00:10:02.276 --> 00:10:05.374
"A free world-class education for anyone anywhere."

00:10:05.374 --> 00:10:08.723
To a certain degree, the free part is part of our mission.

00:10:08.723 --> 00:10:12.442
Yes, we intend to always have it to be free.

00:10:12.442 --> 00:10:16.599
Which raises the question of, "How are you going to support yourself?"

00:10:16.629 --> 00:10:20.872
Obviously, right now, we're foundation and philanthropically supported.

00:10:20.872 --> 00:10:23.123
Hopefully, we can figure out ways.

00:10:23.123 --> 00:10:27.373
We've already started licensing our content to for-profit companies

00:10:27.373 --> 00:10:29.276
who want to use it for other purposes.

00:10:29.276 --> 00:10:32.373
We think there are ways that we can keep the mission sacred

00:10:32.373 --> 00:10:36.526
and keep it free, so that learning really is, it's an equal playing field.

00:10:36.526 --> 00:10:43.110
Diane: Clearly, what you're talking about, the model you've mention,

00:10:43.110 --> 00:10:51.623
is sort of flipping the classroom, so that kids can study at home,

00:10:51.623 --> 00:10:55.525
do their homework in the classroom.

00:10:55.525 --> 00:10:57.194
How does that work?

00:10:57.194 --> 00:11:01.378
Salman: To be clear, none of the ides that I talk about are kind of the medal level

00:11:01.378 --> 00:11:03.825
or even in the book, are new ideas.

00:11:03.825 --> 00:11:08.861
To a large degree, they came to us from teachers or from parents or from students.

00:11:08.861 --> 00:11:13.002
In these realy days, 2007, 2008, I started getting letters from teachers

00:11:13.002 --> 00:11:16.159
and they started talking about this idea of flipping the classroom.

00:11:16.159 --> 00:11:20.608
You've given a lecture on meiosis, you've given a lecture on photosynthesis,

00:11:20.608 --> 00:11:23.253
or on factoring a polynomial,

00:11:23.253 --> 00:11:26.824
I don't have to use this valuable class time doing that anymore

00:11:26.824 --> 00:11:30.362
and doing it at the set pace, some of the kids are lost, some of them are board.

00:11:30.362 --> 00:11:34.236
Instead, they can watch your stuff at their own time, at their own pace,

00:11:34.236 --> 00:11:36.502
and other resources that are out there.

00:11:36.502 --> 00:11:39.753
They come to class time and they can do true problem solving, true interactivity.

00:11:39.753 --> 00:11:45.641
Diane: Salman Khan, founder of the Khan Academy, his new book,

00:11:45.641 --> 00:11:49.764
The One World Schoolhouse.

00:11:49.764 --> 00:11:52.057
Short break, right back.

00:11:52.057 --> 00:11:54.182
(orchestra music)

00:12:08.213 --> 00:12:10.816
(upbeat music)

00:13:08.365 --> 00:13:13.033
Diane: Here's our first email for Salman Khan,

00:13:13.033 --> 00:13:21.244
author of the new book titled, The One World Schoolhouse Education Reimagined.

00:13:21.244 --> 00:13:25.012
Here's an email from Carol, who says,

00:13:25.012 --> 00:13:32.632
"I'm working with a computer savvy inmate and open-minded staff members"

00:13:32.632 --> 00:13:37.873
"in a Missouri maximum security prison."

00:13:37.873 --> 00:13:44.259
"We put the Khan system on disc, since the Internet is not allowed,"

00:13:44.259 --> 00:13:48.945
"and it's now being used in GED classes"

00:13:48.945 --> 00:13:54.638
"and being shown throughout the prison on closed circuit TV."

00:13:54.638 --> 00:14:00.517
"Is Mr. Khan aware of this happening in other prisons?"

00:14:00.517 --> 00:14:03.051
"Does he have any suggestions?"

00:14:03.051 --> 00:14:04.762
Salman: That's incredible.

00:14:04.762 --> 00:14:05.873
Diane: Isn't that fabulous?

00:14:05.873 --> 00:14:07.012
Salman: It's great to hear.

00:14:07.012 --> 00:14:08.762
This is how we're discovering things.

00:14:08.762 --> 00:14:12.487
As soon as you allow other ways for the knowledge to kind of get out there

00:14:12.487 --> 00:14:14.890
and people to interact with it, we discover things like this.

00:14:14.890 --> 00:14:18.754
We have heard of other people talk about this idea,

00:14:18.754 --> 00:14:22.616
of being able to reach the prison population.

00:14:22.616 --> 00:14:24.115
This is great to hear that.

00:14:24.115 --> 00:14:28.902
The unfortunate thing is that there is limited or no access to the Internet.

00:14:28.902 --> 00:14:31.241
My suggestion would be to figure out a way

00:14:31.241 --> 00:14:33.740
to give at least limited access to the Internet,

00:14:33.740 --> 00:14:36.991
so that they could benefit from the true interactivity of the site

00:14:36.991 --> 00:14:38.720
and they can get kind of the updated information.

00:14:38.720 --> 00:14:46.361
Diane: That restriction to the Internet, within prisons, is for a good reason.

00:14:46.361 --> 00:14:52.380
What they've done here is to put it on disk and make it happen that way.

00:14:52.380 --> 00:14:55.990
I think that's incredible, that you're reaching in that way.

00:14:55.990 --> 00:14:57.130
Khan: That's great to hear.

00:14:57.130 --> 00:15:01.104
Diane: Here is an email from Justin, who says,

00:15:01.104 --> 00:15:06.614
"I've come to rely heavily on Khan Academy for supplementing"

00:15:06.614 --> 00:15:11.498
"the public school education of my 2 young children."

00:15:11.498 --> 00:15:17.414
"It's the best resource I have found for that purpose."

00:15:17.414 --> 00:15:18.998
Salman: These letters, when we hear stuff like that,

00:15:18.998 --> 00:15:22.664
that's what, in 2008, when there was some temptation

00:15:22.664 --> 00:15:25.754
to turn this into a for-profit company,

00:15:25.754 --> 00:15:29.365
it's letters like that that made me realize, at the time,

00:15:29.365 --> 00:15:34.493
that we can't ever put any barrier to this information or to this knowledge

00:15:34.493 --> 00:15:38.498
and it never be captive to some other motive.

00:15:38.498 --> 00:15:41.618
As many Justin's and Carol's out there, the better.

00:15:41.618 --> 00:15:44.998
Diane: Haven't some people come along to you and said,

00:15:44.998 --> 00:15:47.664
"Sal Khan, you're nuts."

00:15:47.664 --> 00:15:49.831
Salman: All the time. (laughs)

00:15:49.831 --> 00:15:50.997
Diane: Yeah. I'm sure they do.

00:15:50.997 --> 00:15:52.855
Salman: Before Khan Academy too.

00:15:52.855 --> 00:16:01.216
Diane: Yeah. I mean, that you haven't turned this into a for-profit education system

00:16:01.216 --> 00:16:04.111
and made billions.

00:16:04.111 --> 00:16:07.748
Salman: I think there is a -

00:16:07.748 --> 00:16:10.865
Sometimes it's well intentioned, especially in Silicon Valley,

00:16:10.865 --> 00:16:14.729
people believe that true innovation happens in the for-profit sector,

00:16:14.729 --> 00:16:18.716
that only for-profits are lean and nimble and efficient and all of that.

00:16:18.716 --> 00:16:23.625
I think that there's a medal level narrative that we're hoping to prove with Khan Academy.

00:16:23.625 --> 00:16:27.546
One, we're not-for-profit so that we can deliver this information to people.

00:16:27.546 --> 00:16:29.547
There's also a part of me that wants to show people

00:16:29.547 --> 00:16:33.629
that a not-for-profit can scale and be lean and be nimble.

00:16:33.629 --> 00:16:38.379
One thing that we were worried about when we were starting off is,

00:16:38.379 --> 00:16:40.878
okay we're not-for-profit, we have a very great board.

00:16:40.878 --> 00:16:44.274
They say, yes, we should definitely pay people, market salaries, etcetera,

00:16:44.274 --> 00:16:45.441
but we're not going to be able to give stock options,

00:16:45.441 --> 00:16:47.620
because there's no stock.

00:16:47.620 --> 00:16:49.250
No one owns Khan Academy.

00:16:49.250 --> 00:16:52.977
We're like, "Will we be able to compete in Silicon Valley for the best talent,"

00:16:52.977 --> 00:16:56.151
"the best software engineering talent, without options?"

00:16:56.151 --> 00:16:58.880
The answer has been a resounding yes.

00:16:58.880 --> 00:17:01.372
In fact, we've been able to get some of the very best talent.

00:17:01.372 --> 00:17:04.670
Google's first employee, Craig Silverstein, is on our team.

00:17:04.670 --> 00:17:09.501
We have one of Facebook's, one of their great engineers.

00:17:09.501 --> 00:17:12.817
She was also rated the best engineer at Yahoo at one time.

00:17:12.817 --> 00:17:14.377
She's on our team.

00:17:14.377 --> 00:17:17.751
We have folks who are really the leaders in their respective fields,

00:17:17.751 --> 00:17:18.999
all wanting to join our team.

00:17:18.999 --> 00:17:20.751
There was a research study that came out a couple of years ago

00:17:20.751 --> 00:17:23.817
that said, "People actually aren't driven by money."

00:17:23.817 --> 00:17:26.755
"In fact, the way that they get the most productive is,"

00:17:26.755 --> 00:17:29.318
"they should have enough that they're not worried about money;"

00:17:29.318 --> 00:17:32.005
"they can pay their mortgage and they can send their kids to college,"

00:17:32.005 --> 00:17:36.003
"but they need intellectually challenging work and they need a mission."

00:17:36.003 --> 00:17:42.121
It's funny, when I first read that when I was a Hedge Fund analyst,

00:17:42.121 --> 00:17:43.728
I was a little skeptical of that.

00:17:43.728 --> 00:17:46.624
Really, they don't want huge bonuses?

00:17:46.624 --> 00:17:48.254
One, that's true for myself.

00:17:48.254 --> 00:17:50.505
I'm very happy doing what I'm doing,

00:17:50.505 --> 00:17:54.002
but it seems like it's true also for the best talent out there.

00:17:54.002 --> 00:17:57.651
Diane: How many employees do you now have?

00:17:57.651 --> 00:18:01.151
Salman: We're now 36 and it's been a pretty rapid growth curve.

00:18:01.151 --> 00:18:03.233
This time last year we were 13.

00:18:03.233 --> 00:18:06.318
This time 2 years ago we were 1.

00:18:06.318 --> 00:18:09.254
Diane: How do the employees work?

00:18:09.254 --> 00:18:13.127
How does the share of work get divided?

00:18:13.127 --> 00:18:20.151
Are some pure technical, on the technical side and some on the vocational side?

00:18:20.151 --> 00:18:21.650
How do you do it?

00:18:21.650 --> 00:18:28.360
Salman: On one level we are running a large scale Internet piece of software,

00:18:28.360 --> 00:18:30.247
with 7,000,000 users a month now.

00:18:30.247 --> 00:18:36.106
They've done close to a 3/4's of a billion problems on our site.

00:18:36.106 --> 00:18:38.477
We have a pretty deep engineering diametric.

00:18:38.477 --> 00:18:42.111
2/3's of our team are software engineers and designers.

00:18:42.111 --> 00:18:46.039
The other 3rd of our team is some combination of content producers.

00:18:46.039 --> 00:18:48.476
There's myself and I still produce content.

00:18:48.476 --> 00:18:50.121
We've brought some other people on.

00:18:50.121 --> 00:18:54.849
We have art history content that's made by some pretty incredible professors.

00:18:54.849 --> 00:18:58.122
We have a team that interfaces with schools, interfaces with teachers.

00:18:58.122 --> 00:19:00.484
We have some teachers on staff that are advising us,

00:19:00.484 --> 00:19:02.616
helping us curate content.

00:19:02.616 --> 00:19:05.133
We have kind of a research team that's looking at the data

00:19:05.133 --> 00:19:07.384
and figuring out, how can we improve the content.

00:19:07.384 --> 00:19:09.550
They're also looking at the literature out there

00:19:09.550 --> 00:19:14.997
and seeing what type of research can we leverage to make our offering better.

00:19:14.997 --> 00:19:20.997
Diane: Each of your tutorials is just 10 minutes long.

00:19:20.997 --> 00:19:24.876
Why is gravity such an issue?

00:19:24.876 --> 00:19:28.558
Salman: It's one of these things designed by hindsight.

00:19:28.558 --> 00:19:31.483
When I started doing this, I think the first video

00:19:31.483 --> 00:19:34.505
I made for my cousins in 2006 might have been -

00:19:34.505 --> 00:19:35.307
Diane: For Nadia.

00:19:35.307 --> 00:19:37.641
Salman: For Nadia and at this point there were several others.

00:19:37.641 --> 00:19:39.058
It was about 16 minutes.

00:19:39.058 --> 00:19:41.384
I tried to upload it to You Tube and I got rejected,

00:19:41.384 --> 00:19:43.989
because You Tube, at the time, for a regular account,

00:19:43.989 --> 00:19:46.507
would only give you 10 minutes for each video.

00:19:46.507 --> 00:19:48.235
I said, "Well, I guess I have to redo this thing."

00:19:48.235 --> 00:19:49.755
I redid those.

00:19:49.755 --> 00:19:52.255
I think it was 9 1/2 minutes and I uploaded it.

00:19:52.255 --> 00:19:54.058
I did all the videos in that.

00:19:54.058 --> 00:19:57.987
You can cover a lot, because you can do as many videos as you like.

00:19:57.987 --> 00:20:00.006
One, I got feedback from a lot of people

00:20:00.006 --> 00:20:03.630
that this is working for them, it allows them to pay attention.

00:20:03.630 --> 00:20:05.873
Then, I got researchers coming out of the woodworks saying,

00:20:05.873 --> 00:20:10.506
"You must have read, study X, Y and Z, and I cite a lot of them in the book,

00:20:10.506 --> 00:20:15.811
that actually showed that there's no reason to give a lecture more than 10, 15 minutes,

00:20:15.811 --> 00:20:19.736
because people can't pay attention, especially when it's deep content.

00:20:19.736 --> 00:20:23.007
They can do it for 10, 15 minutes, then they need to kind of step out,

00:20:23.007 --> 00:20:26.395
engage with the content, do a little practice or whatever else,

00:20:26.395 --> 00:20:30.883
then maybe step back in and they have - their attention is recharged.

00:20:30.883 --> 00:20:36.888
In hindsight, it actually is backed up by how the brain works.

00:20:36.888 --> 00:20:46.556
Diane: You know - pardon me - I have often said that when I go to church

00:20:46.556 --> 00:20:53.003
11 minutes in and my head is elsewhere after that.

00:20:53.003 --> 00:20:56.632
I think you've hit it exactly right.

00:20:56.632 --> 00:21:03.196
I think our listeners should know that you come from very humble roots.

00:21:03.196 --> 00:21:09.310
You were raised by your mother who is from Bangladesh.

00:21:09.310 --> 00:21:12.531
You attended public schools growing up.

00:21:12.531 --> 00:21:15.445
How did your background shape you?

00:21:15.445 --> 00:21:17.445
Salman: It's hard to say.

00:21:17.445 --> 00:21:23.382
I think, definitely, one thing I cite is my older sister was a very strong student.

00:21:23.382 --> 00:21:25.772
She was 3 years older and I think that -

00:21:25.772 --> 00:21:29.664
When you enter a class and they already thought highly of your sister 3 years ago,

00:21:29.664 --> 00:21:33.580
even if you're a little mediocre, they kind of expect you to step up a little bit.

00:21:33.580 --> 00:21:36.165
I was definitely a beneficiary of that.

00:21:36.165 --> 00:21:39.511
I went to public schools in Louisiana.

00:21:39.511 --> 00:21:42.636
I think the schools I went to, they were kind of the -

00:21:42.636 --> 00:21:45.145
I would call them probably the 50 percentile American school,

00:21:45.145 --> 00:21:46.512
just kind of the traditional school.

00:21:46.512 --> 00:21:49.012
I had teachers across the spectrum,

00:21:49.012 --> 00:21:52.610
but I had some incredible teachers early on.

00:21:52.610 --> 00:21:56.637
I think frankly because my sister kind of blazed this trail,

00:21:56.637 --> 00:21:59.887
I was able to get into these GT programs where -

00:21:59.887 --> 00:22:02.805
A lot of what I talk in the book was motivated by,

00:22:02.805 --> 00:22:07.056
I remember Ms, Roucelle, the first time I entered the GT, I think it was 4th grade.

00:22:07.056 --> 00:22:10.511
The rest of your curriculum is this Prussian model,

00:22:10.511 --> 00:22:12.660
where all the students are being moved together

00:22:12.660 --> 00:22:16.160
and you're getting a lecture and you have these tests and these grades.

00:22:16.160 --> 00:22:19.576
Then all of the sudden, once a day I would be going to this GT class

00:22:19.576 --> 00:22:23.008
and Ms. Roucelle would say, "What do you want to work on?"

00:22:23.008 --> 00:22:27.395
I was like, "She's asking me. I'm 9 years old. What do I want to work on?"

00:22:27.395 --> 00:22:30.310
"All right," I said, "I like to draw."

00:22:30.310 --> 00:22:32.259
She was like, "Okay, we're going to draw then."

00:22:32.259 --> 00:22:34.144
She would push me.

00:22:34.144 --> 00:22:38.258
She would say, "Here's pen and ink, here's pastels, see what you can do here."

00:22:38.258 --> 00:22:39.644
"What else do you like to do?"

00:22:39.644 --> 00:22:41.154
I said, "I like puzzles."

00:22:41.154 --> 00:22:42.753
She would say, "Here's some puzzles."

00:22:42.753 --> 00:22:44.812
She would push me and allow me to go at my own pace

00:22:44.812 --> 00:22:47.397
and give room for my creativity.

00:22:47.397 --> 00:22:51.759
I can't understate how important I think that was.

00:22:51.759 --> 00:22:54.812
I think probably a lot of the ideas in the book, in hindsight are,

00:22:54.812 --> 00:22:58.504
can we get that at scale, can we get that type of interaction,

00:22:58.504 --> 00:23:01.882
shouldn't all classroom activity be what I got to do at Ms. Roucelle.

00:23:01.882 --> 00:23:05.299
Actually, Ms. Krauss was the other GT teacher at that time.

00:23:05.299 --> 00:23:08.995
I think now that there's other ways to deliver the lecture

00:23:08.995 --> 00:23:10.549
and hopefully better ways.

00:23:10.549 --> 00:23:12.880
There's other ways to do a lot of the problem solving.

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:14.377
Every student should have that experience,

00:23:14.377 --> 00:23:17.920
where they go to class and they get that personal attention.

00:23:17.920 --> 00:23:19.878
They get personal attention, not just with their teachers,

00:23:19.878 --> 00:23:21.170
but also with their peers.

00:23:21.170 --> 00:23:24.920
Right now, you go into a classroom K-12 or in college,

00:23:24.920 --> 00:23:26.789
in K-12 there might be 30 people in the room,

00:23:26.789 --> 00:23:28.667
in college it might be 300.

00:23:28.667 --> 00:23:31.085
You're in the room together, often for the whole year,

00:23:31.085 --> 00:23:32.335
you don't know anybody.

00:23:32.335 --> 00:23:33.169
You don't get to talk.

00:23:33.169 --> 00:23:35.007
Maybe you know the 2 people who you sit next to.

00:23:35.007 --> 00:23:38.382
It's actually very dehumanizing to be in a room and not know the people in the room.

00:23:38.382 --> 00:23:40.760
What we say is, "No, let's remove that lecture."

00:23:40.760 --> 00:23:43.867
"There's no good reason, especially a 300 person lecture,

00:23:43.867 --> 00:23:46.633
and use all of that for interactivity, use all of that for peer to peer learning,

00:23:46.633 --> 00:23:49.756
use all of that for interacting with the professor.

00:23:49.756 --> 00:23:58.878
Diane: Are you as worried as some people are, educators, in this country

00:23:58.878 --> 00:24:05.237
about what has happened to our students?

00:24:05.237 --> 00:24:07.510
Salman: I won't say that I'm not worried.

00:24:07.510 --> 00:24:12.507
One should never be complacent about something as important as education.

00:24:12.507 --> 00:24:16.670
With that said, I think some of the concern is misguided.

00:24:16.670 --> 00:24:21.556
What people always cite is where we are on these test scores relative to other countries

00:24:21.556 --> 00:24:23.889
and Estonia is beating us, their algebra students

00:24:23.889 --> 00:24:25.610
can factor polynomials better than ours.

00:24:25.610 --> 00:24:28.003
That's worth looking at.

00:24:28.003 --> 00:24:30.387
I think and I've heard people say,

00:24:30.387 --> 00:24:33.389
"How can we be more like Singapore, how can we be more like Finland,"

00:24:33.389 --> 00:24:34.884
"be more like South Korea."

00:24:34.884 --> 00:24:37.008
I take a completely different view on it.

00:24:37.008 --> 00:24:41.490
If you look at the U.S. holistically, 50 years ago,

00:24:41.490 --> 00:24:44.218
and there still is innovation happening all the world,

00:24:44.218 --> 00:24:46.382
but the U.S. was a significant chunk of it,

00:24:46.382 --> 00:24:49.717
but it was happening in Europe, Japan and everywhere.

00:24:49.717 --> 00:24:53.239
You look now, the innovation has gotten even more concentrated in the U.S.

00:24:53.239 --> 00:24:55.009
We were worried about Sony.

00:24:55.009 --> 00:24:55.864
I mean, Sony is still a great company,

00:24:55.864 --> 00:24:58.382
but now Apple is owning consumer electronics.

00:24:58.382 --> 00:25:00.883
You have the Googles, the Facebooks, all of the innovative,

00:25:00.883 --> 00:25:06.755
the Twitters, they're all getting created in this culture, in America.

00:25:06.755 --> 00:25:08.732
It's because we have a culture of entrepreneurship,

00:25:08.732 --> 00:25:10.005
we have a culture of innovation,

00:25:10.005 --> 00:25:13.166
we have a culture of not caring what family you're from,

00:25:13.166 --> 00:25:15.003
but really what you can do.

00:25:15.003 --> 00:25:19.128
A culture of taking risk and failure is acceptable.

00:25:19.128 --> 00:25:21.103
A culture of creativity.

00:25:21.103 --> 00:25:25.878
I actually think the task is not how do we get our school system

00:25:25.878 --> 00:25:30.265
to emulate the Prussian model as implemented in Singapore or Finland,

00:25:30.265 --> 00:25:33.499
it's how do we break the Prussian model and make it more American,

00:25:33.499 --> 00:25:35.387
so that we can have creativity in the class time,

00:25:35.387 --> 00:25:39.246
so that all of these things that make America a great engine of innovation

00:25:39.246 --> 00:25:41.138
are actually happening in the classroom as well.

00:25:41.138 --> 00:25:52.130
Diane: Salmon Khan, his knew book is titled, The One World Schoolhouse Education Reimagined.

00:25:52.130 --> 00:25:55.797
You're listening to the Diane Rehm Show.

00:25:55.797 --> 00:25:58.223
Salman, look at the dropout rate.

00:25:58.223 --> 00:26:04.123
Look at the number of young people who are so turned off

00:26:04.123 --> 00:26:10.130
by what's happening in the classroom that some have predicted

00:26:10.130 --> 00:26:17.380
that eventually the U.S. is going to have only a small portion

00:26:17.380 --> 00:26:26.630
of the population, able to create these new systems to move the country forward.

00:26:26.630 --> 00:26:31.999
How do we close that education gap?

00:26:31.999 --> 00:26:33.128
Salman: I think you hit the nail on the head.

00:26:33.128 --> 00:26:34.379
That is the main issue.

00:26:34.379 --> 00:26:37.047
The U.S. won't lose it's dominance or it's innovation,

00:26:37.047 --> 00:26:39.980
but who gets to participate in that -
450
00:26:39,980 --&gt; 00:26:39,878
Diane: Right.

00:26:39.878 --> 00:26:41.130
Salman: - in that question.

00:26:41.130 --> 00:26:44.379
That's why, and I keep hitting on it in the book,

00:26:44.379 --> 00:26:49.129
we have this model where we group students in this kind of factory,

00:26:49.129 --> 00:26:51.728
we group them in these age based cohorts.

00:26:51.728 --> 00:26:55.129
We push them along and we have a set time and pace

00:26:55.129 --> 00:26:57.047
when they're supposed to learn certain things.

00:26:57.047 --> 00:27:01.502
Week 3 in algebra course, we're covering quadratics.

00:27:01.502 --> 00:27:05.186
The information is delivered, some homework happens

00:27:05.186 --> 00:27:06.870
and then there's a test.

00:27:06.870 --> 00:27:10.482
Some students get an A, some get a B, some get a C, some even fail the exam.

00:27:10.482 --> 00:27:12.909
Even though we've identified these gaps in the knowledge

00:27:12.909 --> 00:27:14.489
I mean, some students failed the exam because of the way the system is architected 

00:27:14.489 --> 00:27:18.266
we push them all forward.

00:27:18.266 --> 00:27:21.767
Somehow expecting the student who got the C or the D or the F in basic concept

00:27:21.767 --> 00:27:24.184
to now be able to comprehend the next one.

00:27:24.184 --> 00:27:29.518
Essentially, whenever you have everyone - the delivery happening at a set pace,

00:27:29.518 --> 00:27:31.528
it's really just a filtering process.

00:27:31.528 --> 00:27:34.029
Imagine a factory line.

00:27:34.029 --> 00:27:35.883
The factory line is moving at a set pace.

00:27:35.883 --> 00:27:37.744
It doesn't matter if there are defects emerging.

00:27:37.744 --> 00:27:40.023
A good factory would go and fix the defects.

00:27:40.023 --> 00:27:41.635
In this factory line, you keep moving along.

00:27:41.635 --> 00:27:43.023
At different points you're like,

00:27:43.023 --> 00:27:44.939
"Hey that's getting a little defective. Let's put it on a different line."

00:27:44.939 --> 00:27:46.438
That's not going to be a high-end product.

00:27:46.438 --> 00:27:47.772
That's going to be a low product.

00:27:47.772 --> 00:27:49.190
It's a whole filtering process.

00:27:49.190 --> 00:27:51.440
In the end you will only end up with 5% of people

00:27:51.440 --> 00:27:55.538
who can really participate in kind of the innovation economy.

00:27:55.538 --> 00:27:57.358
What we're saying is, that makes no sense,

00:27:57.358 --> 00:28:00.371
especially in a world where we need so many people who are creative,

00:28:00.371 --> 00:28:02.788
who are active problem solvers.

00:28:02.788 --> 00:28:05.776
We need to do it the other way around.

00:28:05.776 --> 00:28:09.276
Instead of being variable, what your grade is and being fixed when you learn it,

00:28:09.276 --> 00:28:12.372
we need to make variable when and how you learn it,

00:28:12.372 --> 00:28:13.884
spend as much time as you need to.

00:28:13.884 --> 00:28:16.260
What's fixed is, you master the concept.

00:28:16.260 --> 00:28:19.943
It's much more important to have mastery of algebra,

00:28:19.943 --> 00:28:22.383
than to have a superficial understanding of algebra

00:28:22.383 --> 00:28:24.276
and then a superficial understanding of geometry

00:28:24.276 --> 00:28:26.366
and then a very superficial understanding of trigonometry

00:28:26.366 --> 00:28:28.276
and barely getting through calculus.

00:28:28.276 --> 00:28:32.634
Once you really understand algebra, then the rest of it will seem intuitive.

00:28:32.634 --> 00:28:39.872
Diane: If you're at home looking at this tutorial,

00:28:39.872 --> 00:28:49.570
say you've had to watch 2 or 3 times and you still don't quite get it,

00:28:49.570 --> 00:28:51.497
then what happens?

00:28:51.497 --> 00:28:53.812
Salman: This is something that we're constantly trying to address.

00:28:53.812 --> 00:28:57.212
Frankly, this is why we think there is always -

00:28:57.212 --> 00:28:59.133
the human element will always be very important.

00:28:59.133 --> 00:29:01.794
We're trying to address it virtually.

00:29:01.794 --> 00:29:05.010
Hopefully there's multiple tutorials on that same topic.

00:29:05.010 --> 00:29:08.212
We're exploring getting other people involved.

00:29:08.212 --> 00:29:09.795
My style might work for a lot of people,

00:29:09.795 --> 00:29:11.633
but maybe it doesn't gel with other people.

00:29:11.633 --> 00:29:12.961
We get other people there.

00:29:12.961 --> 00:29:14.635
There's a community of learners on the site.

00:29:14.635 --> 00:29:16.261
People can ask questions.

00:29:16.261 --> 00:29:19.295
"I just don't get this. What else should I look at?"

00:29:19.295 --> 00:29:20.883
People will either answer it in text,

00:29:20.883 --> 00:29:24.794
or they'll send a link to another, maybe, video on You Tube some place

00:29:24.794 --> 00:29:27.362
or Wikipedia article, to help explain it.

00:29:27.362 --> 00:29:29.859
The real ideal, I have young children

00:29:29.859 --> 00:29:32.636
and I want them to have access to a physical school.

00:29:32.636 --> 00:29:35.774
What this would do is set up the question.

00:29:35.774 --> 00:29:39.690
If the student can't get an answer in any of these initial lines of attack,

00:29:39.690 --> 00:29:42.495
then they can go to school and that's what the classroom is about.

00:29:42.495 --> 00:29:43.774
It's not about lecture.

00:29:43.774 --> 00:29:48.616
It's about, "Teacher, I have this question" or "Friend, I have this question."

00:29:48.616 --> 00:29:50.275
Obviously, then the friend can help them.

00:29:50.275 --> 00:29:54.373
Also, the process of explaining the answer allows that friend to get it much deeper.

00:29:54.373 --> 00:29:58.277
Diane: Have you yet had an opportunity to talk

