00:33:08.868 --> 00:33:15.263
Diane: We're back with Salman Khan, founder of The Khan Academy.

00:33:15.263 --> 00:33:20.431
During the break I was asking just how far

00:33:20.431 --> 00:33:23.367
you think you can take this concept.

00:33:23.367 --> 00:33:27.474
You start, perhaps in elementary school.

00:33:27.474 --> 00:33:33.120
Do you think you can take it to law school, to medical school, what?

00:33:33.120 --> 00:33:35.262
Salman: Yeah, we already have, especially and the video side

00:33:35.262 --> 00:33:37.357
and we hope of the interactive side soon,

00:33:37.357 --> 00:33:40.617
we already have content, I would say, at the university level

00:33:40.617 --> 00:33:44.989
in the sciences and mathematics, in art history.

00:33:44.989 --> 00:33:48.724
We're already starting to work at some graduate level topics.

00:33:48.724 --> 00:33:51.993
We have a gentleman, Rishi Desai, who is a medical doctor,

00:33:51.993 --> 00:33:54.512
starting to cover the first 2 years of medical school.

00:33:54.512 --> 00:33:57.096
On Khan Academy, we've been working with Stanford Medical School,

00:33:57.096 --> 00:34:00.742
thinking about how they can release more content in this way.

00:34:00.742 --> 00:34:06.242
Our general sense is, we think almost anything can be covered like this

00:34:06.242 --> 00:34:08.180
and not just a graduate level.

00:34:08.180 --> 00:34:10.117
We can even go to lifelong learning topics.

00:34:10.117 --> 00:34:13.180
Diane: Okay. Let me understand something.

00:34:13.180 --> 00:34:21.493
Stanford University gets involved and they have students paying tution

00:34:21.493 --> 00:34:23.656
to go to medical school.

00:34:23.656 --> 00:34:31.474
If they then use Khan Academy, how do they make up for the loss of tuition,

00:34:31.474 --> 00:34:39.406
or do they become the for-profit part of your nonprofit institution?

00:34:39.406 --> 00:34:42.867
Salman: Stanford is also a not-for-profit.

00:34:42.867 --> 00:34:44.118
They charge a lot of tuition.

00:34:44.118 --> 00:34:45.118
Diane: Yeah, you bet.

00:34:45.118 --> 00:34:47.493
Salman: No one owns Stanford University.

00:34:47.493 --> 00:34:49.905
It's not a company.

00:34:49.905 --> 00:34:52.618
I think they understand what this is about.

00:34:52.618 --> 00:34:55.405
This isn't about virtual replacing physical.

00:34:55.405 --> 00:34:59.407
This is about virtual being used as a tool to make physical more powerful.

00:34:59.407 --> 00:35:01.100
They've already recognized.

00:35:01.100 --> 00:35:05.008
They've actually been videotaping a lot of their lectures for several years now.

00:35:05.008 --> 00:35:07.871
A lot of their students prefer to watch that at their own time and pace.

00:35:07.871 --> 00:35:10.423
They're like, "Why are we even going through this exercise?"

00:35:10.423 --> 00:35:12.671
"Let's make really good lectures, make them interactive,"

00:35:12.671 --> 00:35:15.260
"put them in these nuggets, so that they're easier to digest.'

00:35:15.260 --> 00:35:17.508
"Embed interactive exercises with them."

00:35:17.508 --> 00:35:20.923
When the students get together in the class, with the professors,

00:35:20.923 --> 00:35:24.010
with the TA's, they can do something higher order.

00:35:24.010 --> 00:35:25.628
They can look at a case study.

00:35:25.628 --> 00:35:28.258
They can have a conversation about cases, they can do a lab,

00:35:28.258 --> 00:35:30.800
they can do a project.

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:33.494
In their mind, it allows the physical experience to become more valid,

00:35:33.494 --> 00:35:35.244
in my mind as well.

00:35:35.244 --> 00:35:36.287
They leverage the technology.

00:35:36.287 --> 00:35:38.289
They're not getting replaced by it.

00:35:38.289 --> 00:35:43.287
Diane: You mentioned continuing education.

00:35:43.287 --> 00:35:46.619
There's a email from Dan, who says,

00:35:46.619 --> 00:35:51.224
"Thank you Salman for helping me with statistics."

00:35:51.224 --> 00:35:56.771
"Your method of teaching a complicated subject is greatly appreciated"

00:35:56.771 --> 00:35:59.474
"to a returning student."

00:35:59.474 --> 00:36:03.271
"I love your drawings with many colors."

00:36:03.271 --> 00:36:06.210
"I love your voice, it's sincere."

00:36:06.210 --> 00:36:09.523
"I love your motivating style."

00:36:09.523 --> 00:36:15.865
Dan identifies himself as a returning student at 60.

00:36:15.865 --> 00:36:17.365
Salman: Oh! That's great to hear.

00:36:17.365 --> 00:36:19.023
Diane: Isn't that wonderful?

00:36:19.023 --> 00:36:21.597
All right, let's open the phones.

00:36:21.597 --> 00:36:26.271
First, to Wichita, Kansas and to Cynthia.

00:36:26.271 --> 00:36:27.617
Good morning to you.

00:36:27.617 --> 00:36:29.619
Cynthia: Good morning, Diane.

00:36:29.619 --> 00:36:30.936
You sound wonderful.

00:36:30.936 --> 00:36:32.865
Diane: Thank you.

00:36:32.865 --> 00:36:35.590
Cynthia: My question is, I'm 54 and I'm unemployed,

00:36:35.590 --> 00:36:39.112
but I still like to mess with my brain and keep it ticking.

00:36:39.112 --> 00:36:45.271
I'm just one of those persons that was lucky she got passed through high school.

00:36:45.271 --> 00:36:50.938
I was wondering if Mr. Khan is thinking about helping people like this,

00:36:50.938 --> 00:36:54.438
that don't go to school or can't go to college because we can't afford it

00:36:54.438 --> 00:36:56.365
and we're in our late 50s.

00:36:56.365 --> 00:37:00.523
Is there a program that we can get on and kind of relearn?

00:37:00.523 --> 00:37:01.976
Salman: Yeah, absolutely.

00:37:01.976 --> 00:37:04.990
Everything that we're talking about, even in our organization,

00:37:04.990 --> 00:37:07.771
we never talk about - We're careful about students.

00:37:07.771 --> 00:37:10.115
We say students of all ages.

00:37:10.115 --> 00:37:11.271
A lot of people are surprised.

00:37:11.271 --> 00:37:13.521
Obviously, there's a lot of high school and college students using us,

00:37:13.521 --> 00:37:15.992
but there's a lot of people well into adulthood,

00:37:15.992 --> 00:37:19.240
who are using us to understand academic topics,

00:37:19.240 --> 00:37:24.528
or understand things; what it a financial crisis or how does a bank work

00:37:24.528 --> 00:37:27.521
or what's a credit default swap and things like that.

00:37:27.521 --> 00:37:29.367
The simple answer, Cynthia, is yeah, absolutely.

00:37:29.367 --> 00:37:32.617
I think the site, you would enjoy it as it is.

00:37:32.617 --> 00:37:34.737
One thing that we are exploring is,

00:37:34.737 --> 00:37:39.521
if there are sites like Khan Academy, that can do the learning part for free,

00:37:39.521 --> 00:37:41.715
how do people prove that they've learned it.

00:37:41.715 --> 00:37:45.438
Then, they can take that into the market place and show an employee,

00:37:45.438 --> 00:37:51.501
"Look, I'm just as sharp as the 22-year-old who just graduated from a good university.

00:37:51.501 --> 00:37:55.469
We are exploring that, some ways to give what I would call micro -

00:37:55.469 --> 00:37:57.510
Diane: Some kind of certificate.

00:37:57.510 --> 00:37:59.117
Salman: Yeah, and making it valuable.

00:37:59.117 --> 00:37:59.760
Diane: Yeah.

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:01.115
Salman: There are some programs.

00:38:01.115 --> 00:38:04.594
Some of these MIT Harvard have launched this edX initiative

00:38:04.594 --> 00:38:06.238
where they are giving certificates.

00:38:06.238 --> 00:38:09.510
Actually Cynthia, I would encourage you to look at them as well.

00:38:09.510 --> 00:38:11.106
We want to look at that as well.

00:38:11.106 --> 00:38:13.800
The education is several things.

00:38:13.800 --> 00:38:15.102
It's definitely learning, that's the biggest part.

00:38:15.102 --> 00:38:16.608
There's a community aspect to it,

00:38:16.608 --> 00:38:18.427
but then there's a credentialing aspect to it.

00:38:18.427 --> 00:38:22.865
We want to enable you to learn, but also prove to the market place

00:38:22.865 --> 00:38:24.927
that you can contribute.

00:38:24.927 --> 00:38:28.510
Diane: How does she get to the Khan Academy?

00:38:28.510 --> 00:38:30.617
Salman: It's just khanacademy.org.

00:38:30.617 --> 00:38:34.510
Diane: .org, and then you move around?

00:38:34.510 --> 00:38:36.760
Salman: Yeah. People can search for the content.

00:38:36.760 --> 00:38:39.508
If they know what they're looking for, they can go by topic.

00:38:39.508 --> 00:38:41.847
They can start practicing the interactive exercises

00:38:41.847 --> 00:38:44.100
and that will work them through.

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:45.867
Start 1 + 1 and they'll just keep going

00:38:45.867 --> 00:38:48.510
as they progress to trigonometry or calculus.

00:38:48.510 --> 00:38:49.510
Diane: Fantastic.

00:38:49.510 --> 00:38:51.510
Salman: There's computer science that students can work on.

00:38:51.510 --> 00:38:53.969
Diane: All right, to Rochester, New York.

00:38:53.969 --> 00:38:55.510
Good morning Wilma.

00:38:55.510 --> 00:38:56.760
Wilma: Good morning.

00:38:56.760 --> 00:39:01.365
You covered a lot of what I was going to talk about.

00:39:01.365 --> 00:39:05.099
I find this so exciting.

00:39:05.099 --> 00:39:07.427
Some parents, when they look at their newborn,

00:39:07.427 --> 00:39:09.778
they ask that question, "Are you the one?"

00:39:09.778 --> 00:39:16.260
I think your parents must be saying, "Absolutely yes, you are the one."

00:39:16.260 --> 00:39:18.619
Salman: You're making a brown man blush.

00:39:18.619 --> 00:39:21.354
Diane: (laughs) That's wonderful.

00:39:21.354 --> 00:39:23.510
Thanks for your call, Wilma.

00:39:23.510 --> 00:39:27.510
Let's go to Lewisville, Texas.

00:39:27.510 --> 00:39:29.260
Good Morning, Bret.

00:39:29.260 --> 00:39:30.233
Bret: Good morning, Diane.

00:39:30.233 --> 00:39:31.117
This is a great show.

00:39:31.117 --> 00:39:32.367
I really appreciate you doing it.

00:39:32.367 --> 00:39:33.865
Diane: Thank you.

00:39:33.865 --> 00:39:37.724
Bret: Khan, I've got to tell you, you have really helped my nephew, tremendously.

00:39:37.724 --> 00:39:40.899
I recommended his site to you when he was trying to get -

00:39:40.899 --> 00:39:42.125
He's still trying to get his GED,

00:39:42.125 --> 00:39:44.793
but he was actually getting a lot of help he could get before.

00:39:44.793 --> 00:39:46.271
That's a huge thing.

00:39:46.271 --> 00:39:51.521
I was curious if you are putting forth any effort to educate people

00:39:51.521 --> 00:39:54.878
as to the education system that we have now

00:39:54.878 --> 00:39:57.876
that has this over reliance on testing.

00:39:57.876 --> 00:39:59.523
If you've put any effort into that

00:39:59.523 --> 00:40:03.626
or if you're just focusing on the Khan Academy?

00:40:03.626 --> 00:40:06.128
Salman: That's a great question, Bret.

00:40:06.128 --> 00:40:09.001
It's wonderful to hear about your nephew.

00:40:09.001 --> 00:40:10.753
There's a chapter in the book where I talk about testing.

00:40:10.753 --> 00:40:13.795
I think testing will always exist to some degree,

00:40:13.795 --> 00:40:16.246
but I think over alliance is the right word.

00:40:16.246 --> 00:40:19.628
Tests only measure what they test.

00:40:19.628 --> 00:40:23.294
I think what's exciting about what we're doing or hopefully doing

00:40:23.294 --> 00:40:25.208
or at least bringing up in a conversation,

00:40:25.208 --> 00:40:31.126
is what are other ways of measuring or evaluating subjective and objective.

00:40:31.126 --> 00:40:35.626
One thing that I talk a great deal about when I talk to people,

00:40:35.626 --> 00:40:40.501
is test measure one thing, can we measure perseverance.

00:40:40.501 --> 00:40:42.376
In a traditional test, you can't.

00:40:42.376 --> 00:40:43.626
On something like Khan Academy, you can.

00:40:43.626 --> 00:40:46.626
We can see how the student it engaging with the site.

00:40:46.626 --> 00:40:49.044
We can give that feedback to teachers.

00:40:49.044 --> 00:40:53.294
We can cater the content for different types of learners in different ways.

00:40:53.294 --> 00:40:55.626
Can we measure people, instead of these numeric test,

00:40:55.626 --> 00:40:57.727
also with a portfolio of creative works.

00:40:57.727 --> 00:40:59.794
To a large degree, when we hire people at Khan Academy,

00:40:59.794 --> 00:41:03.994
yeah test scores are nice and grades are nice and degrees are nice,

00:41:03.994 --> 00:41:06.863
but we say, "What have you created? Show us your creations."

00:41:06.863 --> 00:41:08.751
"Tell us how you thought about those creations."

00:41:08.751 --> 00:41:11.487
That is at least or far more important than test.

00:41:11.487 --> 00:41:14.128
The other dimension that I think it completely lost right now,

00:41:14.128 --> 00:41:18.878
is how much do you contribute and how capable are you contributing

00:41:18.878 --> 00:41:23.253
to improving the learning of those around you.

00:41:23.253 --> 00:41:26.534
One thing I talk a lot about in the book and we try to foster on the site

00:41:26.534 --> 00:41:28.628
and we're seeing a lot in the classrooms that are using this,

00:41:28.628 --> 00:41:31.784
is students helping each other and evaluating each other,

00:41:31.784 --> 00:41:34.128
saying, "That was really great. They really helped me."

00:41:34.128 --> 00:41:38.291
I hope in the kind of college transcript of the future, yes they'll be a few test scores,

00:41:38.291 --> 00:41:42.313
maybe you'll take these micro credentials that we were talking about,

00:41:42.313 --> 00:41:45.897
to show that you've mastered algebra and you've retained that knowledge.

00:41:45.897 --> 00:41:47.313
You would also have an evaluation,

00:41:47.313 --> 00:41:49.646
"Wow! You've really contributed to other people's learning"

00:41:49.646 --> 00:41:51.897
"and you have this really great portfolio of creative works."

00:41:51.897 --> 00:41:55.064
Diane: Here is an email from R. John.

00:41:55.064 --> 00:42:03.897
He says, "How does the Khan Academy teach and grade good writing?"

00:42:03.897 --> 00:42:06.014
Salman: That's a great question.

00:42:06.014 --> 00:42:08.314
Right now, we don't tackle writing.

00:42:08.314 --> 00:42:11.888
On the video side we tackle a few of the humanities, especially on art history

00:42:11.888 --> 00:42:13.136
and we have a little bit on history.

00:42:13.136 --> 00:42:14.763
We hope to do a lot more.

00:42:14.763 --> 00:42:17.385
I'll tell you how we're envisioning tackling writing

00:42:17.385 --> 00:42:20.705
and I'll start with how we're tackling computer science, which might seem strange.

00:42:20.705 --> 00:42:26.204
Our computer science, we're tackling it as a creative field, which it is.

00:42:26.204 --> 00:42:28.135
Students can go there.

00:42:28.135 --> 00:42:30.382
They can create their programs, interact with it.

00:42:30.382 --> 00:42:32.538
They have a little canvas where they see what they've created.

00:42:32.538 --> 00:42:33.798
Then, they can share it.

00:42:33.798 --> 00:42:35.248
That's an important point.

00:42:35.248 --> 00:42:36.799
When they share it on their portfolio,

00:42:36.799 --> 00:42:38.498
then other users can look at their work,

00:42:38.498 --> 00:42:40.852
they can comment on it, they can rate their work.

00:42:40.852 --> 00:42:43.382
They can take that and then make it their own.

00:42:43.382 --> 00:42:46.131
We think the same analogy can apply with writing.

00:42:46.131 --> 00:42:50.298
You go, there's projects on Khan Academy, write your opinion about this

00:42:50.298 --> 00:42:51.749
or write a novel, write a short story.

00:42:51.749 --> 00:42:54.248
You put it out there, it goes into your portfolio.

00:42:54.248 --> 00:42:56.132
Instead of getting graded, oh you got a B+,

00:42:56.132 --> 00:42:59.548
and then that's kind of a value statement on your intelligence or something -

00:42:59.548 --> 00:43:00.913
Diane: Or somebody else's ...

00:43:00.913 --> 00:43:01.858
Salman: Exactly.

00:43:01.858 --> 00:43:04.761
Diane: ... interpretation of your intelligence.

00:43:04.761 --> 00:43:07.383
Salman: Other people will comment on it, give it feedback

00:43:07.383 --> 00:43:11.162
and you can continuously improve it, so that it becomes part of your portfolio.

00:43:11.162 --> 00:43:13.260
In order to get feedback from other people,

00:43:13.260 --> 00:43:15.009
you will also give feedback.

00:43:15.009 --> 00:43:16.852
By just critically looking at other people's work,

00:43:16.852 --> 00:43:19.312
that will also hopefully make you a better writer.

00:43:19.312 --> 00:43:22.061
I think we can tackle some of the building blocks of writing,

00:43:22.061 --> 00:43:23.643
whether it's vocabulary and grammar,

00:43:23.643 --> 00:43:26.993
in a way that we're tackling some of the building blocks of mathematics.

00:43:26.993 --> 00:43:29.744
Diane: To Easton, Maryland.

00:43:29.744 --> 00:43:31.243
Good morning, Rebecca.

00:43:31.243 --> 00:43:32.311
Rebecca: Good morning.

00:43:32.311 --> 00:43:33.356
Thanks for taking my call.

00:43:33.356 --> 00:43:34.231
Diane: Sure.

00:43:34.231 --> 00:43:37.606
Rebecca: I just wanted to bring in the homeschooling perspective,

00:43:37.606 --> 00:43:44.394
because I homeschool my 2 children, who are in 5th and 3rd grade, perspectively.

00:43:44.394 --> 00:43:48.246
We absolutely love The Khan Academy as a resource

00:43:48.246 --> 00:43:52.625
for those 10 to 12 minutes snipits, especially for math and science.

00:43:52.625 --> 00:43:54.876
They really kind of hit the lesson home.

00:43:54.876 --> 00:43:58.677
It's just a great resource for homeschoolers,

00:43:58.677 --> 00:44:00.261
because it's -

00:44:00.261 --> 00:44:02.875
I don't have all of the same -

00:44:02.875 --> 00:44:04.677
We'll, right now I'm fine with 3rd and 5th grade,

00:44:04.677 --> 00:44:07.761
but connected to experts who know what they're talking about

00:44:07.761 --> 00:44:12.490
and can really help a lot.

00:44:12.490 --> 00:44:15.498
I think it's a great resource and I really appreciate it.

00:44:15.498 --> 00:44:18.998
Salman: That's incredible to hear, Rebecca.

00:44:18.998 --> 00:44:23.115
I think our whole team gets motivated when we hear stories like this.

00:44:23.115 --> 00:44:24.750
The homeschooling is interesting.

00:44:24.750 --> 00:44:26.532
When I started all of this, I didn't even think about it.

00:44:26.532 --> 00:44:30.373
It's completely obvious that this hopefully is a valuable tool for homeschoolers.

00:44:30.373 --> 00:44:32.374
I think what's really interesting about homerschoolers,

00:44:32.374 --> 00:44:34.748
is they've kind of brought back a lot of -

00:44:34.748 --> 00:44:37.874
The book is called One World Schoolhouse, there's a play on one-room school house.

00:44:37.874 --> 00:44:41.123
There were some really strong advantages there.

00:44:41.123 --> 00:44:45.283
This idea of a more personalized attention, a lot more interactivity,

00:44:45.283 --> 00:44:47.873
a lot more allowing the student to pick the direction

00:44:47.873 --> 00:44:50.282
and take ownership of their own learning.

00:44:50.282 --> 00:44:53.284
I think homeschoolers are kind of the leading edge of

00:44:53.284 --> 00:44:55.373
this new way of thinking about learning.

00:44:55.373 --> 00:44:57.032
Diane: Good luck to you, Rebecca.

00:44:57.032 --> 00:44:58.623
Thanks for calling.

00:44:58.623 --> 00:45:03.735
Here's an email going straight to the title of your book.

00:45:03.735 --> 00:45:08.448
It's from Peter, who says, "I'm curious if you have a strategy"

00:45:08.448 --> 00:45:12.532
"for expanding into emerging market countries,"

00:45:12.532 --> 00:45:19.783
"which have limited Internet penetration and access to computers."

00:45:19.783 --> 00:45:21.532
Salman: Yes. It's something that we have been thinking

00:45:21.532 --> 00:45:24.200
and we're starting to think a lot more about.

00:45:24.200 --> 00:45:25.608
There's a couple of things that we're doing,

00:45:25.608 --> 00:45:27.873
and then I'll talk about the access issue.

00:45:27.873 --> 00:45:30.124
We have had a translation project.

00:45:30.124 --> 00:45:33.283
We've translated to varying degrees, it's 12 languages already.

00:45:33.283 --> 00:45:37.248
The ones that are furtherest along are Spanish, Portuguese, Bengali, Arabic.

00:45:37.248 --> 00:45:40.032
If you go to the bottom of the page on Khan Academy, there's a drop down,

00:45:40.032 --> 00:45:41.123
it says English.

00:45:41.123 --> 00:45:44.448
If you just pick another language, you'll see the video is translated into those languages.

00:45:44.448 --> 00:45:45.873
There's 7,000 videos.

00:45:45.873 --> 00:45:47.865
I shouldn't say translated, they've actually been redone

00:45:47.865 --> 00:45:49.623
to a large degree, in a lot of these other languages.

00:45:49.623 --> 00:45:50.532
Diane: I see.

00:45:50.532 --> 00:45:53.699
Salman: Not the the whole, but just a video component is there.

00:45:53.699 --> 00:45:56.781
That raises the issue, okay, even if we're creating this content,

00:45:56.781 --> 00:46:00.282
a lot of these places, people don't have access to it.

00:46:00.282 --> 00:46:03.123
One, there's a lot of separate groups, NGOs,

00:46:03.123 --> 00:46:05.282
who are taking our content and putting it on DVDs,

00:46:05.282 --> 00:46:08.373
putting it on thumb drives, creating offline versions of the website

00:46:08.373 --> 00:46:10.199
and putting it out there.

00:46:10.199 --> 00:46:11.373
We've heard stories.

00:46:11.373 --> 00:46:14.125
There's an orphanage in Mongolia where some volunteers from Sysco

00:46:14.125 --> 00:46:15.487
went out there and set it up.

00:46:15.487 --> 00:46:19.533
There's a 15-year-old girl, Zia, out there, who started using the resource

00:46:19.533 --> 00:46:21.874
and now she's become our main translator into Mongolian.

00:46:21.874 --> 00:46:24.123
A 15-year-old, I think she's 16 now, orphan girl.

00:46:24.123 --> 00:46:25.225
Diane: Wow.

00:46:25.225 --> 00:46:28.370
Salman: That's kind of an intermediate solution.

00:46:28.370 --> 00:46:35.595
The good thing is, now this kind of education tool can ride more as law that -

00:46:35.595 --> 00:46:38.740
Already in India they're talking about sub $100 tablet devices,

00:46:38.740 --> 00:46:40.242
Internet is getting cheaper and cheaper.

00:46:40.242 --> 00:46:44.494
Even in the book I articulate essentially how right now, in the next year,

00:46:44.494 --> 00:46:47.117
we can, if we have a couple of students sharing computers,

00:46:47.117 --> 00:46:49.617
because we don't think kids should be on the computer all day,

00:46:49.617 --> 00:46:51.275
even in the developing world you could deliver

00:46:51.275 --> 00:46:54.218
this type of experience for a penny a day.

00:46:54.218 --> 00:46:58.775
Diane: You're listening to the Diane Rehm Show.

00:46:58.775 --> 00:47:03.228
What happens to teachers in this process?

00:47:03.228 --> 00:47:06.273
Are you going to put them out of business?

00:47:06.273 --> 00:47:08.367
Salman: Not at all.

00:47:08.367 --> 00:47:10.094
It's a really good point to bring up,

00:47:10.094 --> 00:47:12.744
because whenever people talk about a virtual thing that's scaling,

00:47:12.744 --> 00:47:16.273
amazon.com, they're like, "Oh, that's going to replace the physical thing."

00:47:16.273 --> 00:47:20.941
"They have to get buildings and hire people and all this stuff."

00:47:20.941 --> 00:47:22.613
That might be true for certain things like that,

00:47:22.613 --> 00:47:25.244
but absolutely not for education.

00:47:25.244 --> 00:47:28.273
I think what's happening and we're seeing it with the teachers we're working with,

00:47:28.273 --> 00:47:30.940
a lot of the adoption is happening through teachers.

00:47:30.940 --> 00:47:34.367
They're seeing that it's not replacing them, it's empowering them.

00:47:34.367 --> 00:47:37.121
Instead of having to shepherd students as one pace

00:47:37.121 --> 00:47:40.121
and have this variable understanding,

00:47:40.121 --> 00:47:43.023
they're able leverage class time for more interactivity.

00:47:43.023 --> 00:47:45.367
I always imagine education as a spectrum of things.

00:47:45.367 --> 00:47:48.349
At one end is very wrote learning your multiplication tables

00:47:48.349 --> 00:47:50.369
and your vocabulary.

00:47:50.369 --> 00:47:51.992
At the other spectrum is this kind of never ending,

00:47:51.992 --> 00:47:55.523
open ended creative problem solving, whatever else it might be.

00:47:55.523 --> 00:47:57.604
What Khan Academy, we're going to try to tackle

00:47:57.604 --> 00:48:00.023
as much of the different points of the spectrum as we can,

00:48:00.023 --> 00:48:01.523
but it's an infinite spectrum.

00:48:01.523 --> 00:48:05.367
It frees the humans to tackle the stuff that computers will never be able to do,

00:48:05.367 --> 00:48:08.220
the mentorship, the inspiration, the really understanding

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:10.940
what's going on in that particular student's life,

00:48:10.940 --> 00:48:11.992
that particular student's brain.

00:48:11.992 --> 00:48:16.994
The kind of stuff that Ms. Roucelle had done with me when I was in 4th grade.

00:48:16.994 --> 00:48:22.736
Diane: Lot's of folks have asked how to spell Khan.

00:48:22.736 --> 00:48:30.244
It is K-H-A-N, Khan Academy.

00:48:30.244 --> 00:48:31.490
Salman: Just like Genghis.

00:48:31.490 --> 00:48:32.344
Diane: Like Genghis.

00:48:32.344 --> 00:48:33.242
Salman: (laughs)

00:48:33.242 --> 00:48:34.657
Diane: kahn.org.

00:48:34.657 --> 00:48:36.244
Salman: Maybe I shouldn't have that association.

00:48:36.244 --> 00:48:42.244
Diane: Then, last question about evaluating teachers.

00:48:42.244 --> 00:48:44.994
How do you think that should be done?

00:48:44.994 --> 00:48:47.117
Salman: This is probably -

00:48:47.117 --> 00:48:54.992
It's obviously a kind of a heated topic and frankly where I have the least experience.

00:48:54.992 --> 00:48:56.407
I think it has to be a holistic thing.

00:48:56.407 --> 00:48:57.741
I think it has to be a combination.

00:48:57.741 --> 00:49:02.744
I think test will always be there, test scores will always be there

00:49:02.744 --> 00:49:05.655
and they'll be part of a portfolio of evaluation something.

00:49:05.655 --> 00:49:08.156
I think it goes well beyond that.

00:49:08.156 --> 00:49:10.863
People should be measuring, how do other -

00:49:10.863 --> 00:49:13.241
I don't even want to -

00:49:13.241 --> 00:49:15.243
I could think of a million different ways.

00:49:15.243 --> 00:49:17.110
One thing I point out in the book in some detail,

00:49:17.110 --> 00:49:18.907
is be very skeptical of tests.

00:49:18.907 --> 00:49:21.822
They are sometimes necessary to give you a data point.

00:49:21.822 --> 00:49:23.993
They only measure 1 dimension.

00:49:23.993 --> 00:49:27.915
A test definitely, by itself, should not be the only predictor

00:49:27.915 --> 00:49:31.666
or only value statement on a student or a teacher.

00:49:31.666 --> 00:49:38.249
Diane: What's next on your agenda for The Khan Academy?

00:49:38.249 --> 00:49:41.166
Salman: We're trying to make much richer content simulations.

00:49:41.166 --> 00:49:44.380
We're trying to broaden it, start experimenting with things in the humanities,

00:49:44.380 --> 00:49:47.213
ways for students to answer more open-ended questions,

00:49:47.213 --> 00:49:49.878
their opinions on stuff, how they feel about a piece of art work.

00:49:49.878 --> 00:49:50.546
Diane: That's good.

00:49:50.546 --> 00:49:52.964
Salman: How they feel about a piece of history.

00:49:52.964 --> 00:49:57.046
On top of that, we're looking to open up the platform.

00:49:57.046 --> 00:50:00.296
We have, in house, some people making hopefully great content.

00:50:00.296 --> 00:50:02.796
There's so many people out there, teachers around the world,

00:50:02.796 --> 00:50:05.002
who could also contribute in different ways.

00:50:05.002 --> 00:50:06.505
We're hoping to open that in 6 months

00:50:06.505 --> 00:50:09.503
and hopefully we just grow to a few hundred-million people in the next few years.

00:50:09.503 --> 00:50:21.003
Diane: Salman Khan and his new book is titled The One World Schoolhouse Education Reimagined.

00:50:21.003 --> 00:50:26.654
You can go to khanacademy.org.

00:50:26.654 --> 00:50:29.904
Learn all about the offerings.

00:50:29.904 --> 00:50:34.774
It is spelled K-H-A-N.

00:50:34.774 --> 00:50:36.496
Congratulations.

00:50:36.496 --> 00:50:37.521
Salman: Thanks for having me.

00:50:37.521 --> 00:50:39.277
Diane: Thanks for being here.

00:50:39.277 --> 00:50:41.020
Thanks for listening all.

00:50:41.020 --> 00:50:42.880
I'm Diane Rehm.

00:50:42.880 --> 00:50:44.808
(orchestra music)

